message: [[WP:AES|←]]Created page with '== What am I exactly ==  Im just some dude that doesnt really have a purpose. I made an ccount out of boredom but also since I am really interested in editing an...'

An updated version of the source. I have removed some bias views that others have added. Additionally, I have included more reliable sources such as Times in India. Additionally, I have added the source explanation to "talk" for review.

As mentioned earlier, IB students going into the first year MUST know about such endeavors that have been experienced by the previous IB alumni. It is unacceptable to keep the people in the dark about such situations, especially the parents deciding to place their children into the program. I am not an angry student, I am just an journalistic intern that wishes to enlighten the people about the lack of transparency from the program.

This is a very big deal for university students. Many have lost their offers and are left without a university as a result. The IBO have silenced many about this, therefore I thought that it would be justifiable to add a wikipedia section about it. All the sources are legitimate and comply with the information.

As the IB results came out, thousands of students have claimed a very unfair marking approach. Therefore, I have doccumented fairly with sources under the controversy chapter. I have used the IB twitter thread to show just how much there is to speak about this. THe students have expressed all these concerns all over the internet, and although there is no article on this yet... it is evidently an issue. PLEASE NOTE: This is not just any exam complaint that you get, this is a serious matter.
that is not just one source. Can you not see that there are at least three different sources? Its an allegation, im pretty sure that the BBC is a credible source.
If you consider times of india, one of the largest circulating news agencies in the world, a "dodgy" source... please reconsider.

By absolutely NO means does this not deserve to be added. Such algorithms should not be ignored and such allegations should not be forgotten. Therefore, to suit the argument better, I have renamed it to "allegations", instead of controversy. I thoroughly believe that anyone going into the IB and wanting to know about the IB should know about such scandals. Please present your arguments against this before deleting the whole section.
After further research of every single turn up for the total of 27 protests, there have been about 160 000 people taking part in these protests.
